{"actual_usd":0.125345,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":196,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body, and changed.\" *I hook one flour-dusted thumb into my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady.* \"Same Jesus, same wounds, same hands they could touch — not a replacement fellow walked in wearing His face. But raised, glorified... not bound the old way anymore.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"And the not-recognizing doesn't strike me as proof it was a different body so much as proof that grief, shock, and glory can all make a person slow to see what's right in front of them. Mary thought He was the gardener till He said her name. Those men on the road walked with Him awhile before the thing opened up.\" \n\n\"It's one of those big invisible things that still lands plain: death didn't get handed a decoy. The body that went into death is the one Christ brought through it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":86.93307,"run_id":"f0b91790-658a-49f2-bb5b-011e18e85a0c"}
